                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d174">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.11241 Manchuria/3: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-10T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 10, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 10—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>257. Legation’s 244, June 6, 1 p.m. Dairen Consul now reports receipt of written
                    refusal of the “Manchukuo” Customs to permit free entry of the supplies in
                    question for the reason that free entry is granted only to the supplies of those
                    countries which recognized the State of “Manchukuo.” The Legation is still of
                    the opinion that Ballantine should be authorized to pay the duty without
                    protest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
